## 📂 The Vault : Core Concepts

*Click to expand terminal logs for each architectural pattern.*

\<details\>
\<summary\>\<b\>\<code\>[+] 0x01\_POINTER\_ARITHMETIC.c\</code\>\</b\> (The Matrix Illusions)\</summary\>

### 1\. The Commutative Index Anomaly

Under the compiler's hood, `a[b]` is evaluated as `*(a + b)`. Therefore, index and array identifiers are perfectly commutative.

```c
int arr[] = {10, 20, 30};
printf("%d\n", 1[arr]); // Prints 20. Valid C, horrifying to read.
```

### 2\. Type-Aware Jump Offsets

Pointers are strictly type-aware. `arr` and `&arr` point to the same physical hex address, but hold vastly different system context.

```c
int arr[3] = {1,2,3};
// arr + 1 jumps 4 bytes (to the next int)
// &arr + 1 jumps 12 bytes (skips the entire array block)
```

\</details\>

\<details\>
\<summary\>\<b\>\<code\>[+] 0x02\_MEMORY\_SAFETY.c\</code\>\</b\> (The Danger Zone)\</summary\>

### 1\. Dangling Pointers & Stack Frames

Accessing memory after the OS has reclaimed the stack frame results in undefined behavior (UB).

```c
int* get_data() {
    int a = 10;
    return &a; // FATAL: Returning address of local stack variable
}
```

### 2\. Literal vs Array Mutability (Segfault Trap)

String literals live in the read-only `Data Segment`. Attempting to mutate them causes a hardware-level trap (Segmentation Fault).

```c
char *str = "hello"; 
str[0] = 'H'; // ❌ SEGFAULT: Read-Only Memory

char arr[] = "hello";
arr[0] = 'H'; // ✅ Safe: Array allocated on the Stack
```

\</details\>

\<details\>
\<summary\>\<b\>\<code\>[+] 0x03\_ADVANCED\_PATTERNS.c\</code\>\</b\> (System Architecture)\</summary\>

### 1\. The Decay Rule

When passed to a function, arrays decay into pointers. You lose metadata (size) immediately.

```c
void inspect_memory(int arr[]) {
    // sizeof(arr) == 8 (64-bit pointer size), NOT the array capacity.
}
```

### 2\. Double Pointers (The API Interface)

Essential for mutating reference state inside functions (e.g., allocating memory inside an API call).

```c
void allocate_matrix(int **ptr, size_t size) {
    *ptr = malloc(size * sizeof(int));
}
```

\</details\>

